Alabama Broadband for Students Program Update 9/4/2020

Students enrolled in the National School Lunch Program will receive a letter with a prepaid voucher from the Alabama Broadband Connectivity for Students Program that will cover the cost of equipment, installation, and high-speed internet service through December 30, 2020. The Alabama Department of Economic and Community Affairs is staggering the ABC voucher mailouts. Approximately 250,000 vouchers are scheduled to be mailed next week. The total number of vouchers to be mailed is 450,000.

post_text:
Welcome SRO Flint

Jacksonville City Schools would like to welcome Officer Flint as our latest school resource officer. Flint began working alongside long-time SRO. Chris Jordan at Jacksonville High School today. Officer flint will routinely patrol JHS and Kitty Stone Elementary to keep the campuses free from hazardous and prohibited substances and greet students and staff with a friendly tail wag. Flint's presence in the school results from a partnership between the Jacksonville City Board of Education, the City of Jacksonville, the Jacksonville Police Department, and VWK9.

Welcome, Officer Flint!

post_text:
On Friday, August 28, 2020, an individual in a first-grade class at Kitty Stone Elementary School tested positive for COVID-19. Jacksonville City Schools followed all contact tracing steps
outlined by the Alabama State Department of Education and the Alabama Department of Public Health. All parents of students who were deemed as “close contacts” were notified by school
personnel. The affected classroom is closed and will be sanitized before personnel return.

JCS encourages all parents to monitor students closely for any signs of potential illness. Students should remain home if they are exhibiting any symptoms of COVID-19 including fever, new cough, loss of taste or smell, congestion, headache, diarrhea, sore throat, and fatigue.

If you have questions concerning this situation, please feel free to contact Jacksonville City Schools at 256-782-5682.

--
Mr. Mike Newell
Superintendent
Jacksonville City Schools

August 25, 2020

Out of an abundance of caution, Jacksonville City Schools will continue Phase 2: Blended through Friday, September 11. Our goal is to begin Phase 1: On Campus, face-to-face instruction, on Monday, September 14, 2020.

Thank you for your flexibility and patience.

Mr. Mike Newell

Due to the high numbers of positive COVID-19 cases in Calhoun County, Jacksonville City Schools will begin school in Phase 2: Blended outlined in the JCS Reopening Plan. The school district will temporarily be in Phase 2 for two weeks, starting on Tuesday, August 18 through Monday, August 31st.

In Phase 2: Blended Option, students with the last name starting with the letters of “A” through “L” (Group A) will report to campus for face-to-face instruction on Mondays and Tuesdays. Students with the last name starting with the letters of “M” through “Z” (Group B) will go to school on Thursdays and Fridays. Please see Mr. Newell’s letter and The Learning Framework Options on the Jacksonville City Schools website at https://bit.ly/JCSReopening for more information.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we prepare for a safe opening of school.
text:
Due to the high numbers of positive COVID-19 cases in Calhoun County, Jacksonville City Schools will begin school in Phase 2: Blended outlined in the JCS Reopening Plan. The school district will temporarily be in Phase 2 for two weeks, starting on Tuesday, August 18 through Monday, August 31st.

In Phase 2: Blended Option, students with the last name starting with the letters of “A” through “L” (Group A) will report to campus for face-to-face instruction on Mondays and Tuesdays. Students with the last name starting with the letters of “M” through “Z” (Group B) will go to school on Thursdays and Fridays. Please see Mr. Newell’s letter and The Learning Framework Options on the Jacksonville City Schools website at https://bit.ly/JCSReopening for more information.

Thank you for your patience and understanding as we prepare for a safe opening of school.

post_text: This is a reminder that the first day of school will be Tuesday, August 18, 2020, for traditional and Jacksonville Virtual Academy students. Traditional students may start school in one of the following learning phases: Phase I - On-Campus, Phase II - Blended, or Phase III - Temporary Remote. Please plan ahead and make the appropriate family arrangements for any of the opening phases. Currently, JCS intends to open with on-campus learning; however, it is subject to change with increasing COVID-19 cases in the area. JCS will provide as much advance notice as possible about the opening phase. Refer to the opening plan at www.jcsboe.org for more information.

post_text:
In order to be as transparent as possible in the search for a new Superintendent, the decision has been made to release the candidate names before the board meeting tomorrow.

The Jacksonville City School Board has narrowed its search for a new superintendent to three candidates -

Dr. Gary Gibson, Dr. Pamela Liebenberg, and Mr. Mike Newell.

These three candidates will be interviewed for the position of Superintendent on Thursday, May 14, 2020. The interviews will be conducted via Google Meet and will be streamed live. The times for the interviews are 10:00 AM, 11:30 AM, and 1:00 PM. Links for the live stream will be posted on Thursday before the interviews start. All interviews will be recorded and available on the JCS YouTube channel if you are not able to watch the live stream.

Governor Ivey stated today during a press conference that students in Alabama will not be allowed to receive in-person instruction for the remainder of the school year. She charged the local school districts to develop distance learning plans to address the academic needs of students. The plans must be ready for students on April 6, 2020. Therefore, Jacksonville City Schools is working with the Alabama Department of Education to develop a plan that addresses the remaining critical learning standards.
JCS will provide additional information about the plan in the upcoming days through SchoolCast, Facebook, and the district’s websites.

All field trips, activities, gatherings, and athletics have been canceled through June 5, 2020. Jacksonville High School personnel are currently working on alternate prom and graduation plans for dates after June 5th.

Due to the success of the School Closure Feeding program, the Jacksonville City School District WILL continue accepting new reservations for meal pickup on March 30, 2020. The District will receive additional food deliveries prior to March 30, 2020, to continue to assist in meeting the needs of our community and children during this public health crisis. The reservation form will be available on Wednesday, March 25th on the district website and Facebook page.

If you completed this form prior to March 25th for food pickup on March 30th, please fill out this form again to be counted in the total for meals requested. Drive through pickup will be on Monday, March 30th, 2020 from 9:00 a.m. to 11:00 a.m. at Jacksonville High School.

Any child age 18 and younger may receive pre-packaged breakfasts and lunches. No proof of residence is required. Any child from anywhere may participate.

The Jacksonville City School Family is honored to continue to serve the community’s children.

The Alabama Department of Public Health is in close communication with the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) who is closely monitoring an evolving outbreak caused by the new coronavirus in Wuhan, Hubei Province, China. At this time, no 2019 Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases have been identified in Alabama.

It is important that students and staff with a history of travel or contact to a person with known COVID-19 take every day preventative actions:

1. Stay home when sick.
2. Students and staff who have symptoms of acute respiratory illness are asked to stay home and not come to work until they are free of fever(a fever is considered to be 100.4 or greater) and any other symptoms for at least 24 hours, without the use of fever-reducing or other
symptom-altering medications (e.g. cough suppressants).
3. Seek immediate medical care if symptoms become severe, such as high fever or difficulty breathing.

post_text: Jacksonville City Schools will conduct routine operations on Tuesday, February 11, 2020, unless city-wide flooding creates extremely hazardous driving conditions for students, parents, faculty, and staff. text: Jacksonville City Schools will conduct routine operations on Tuesday, February 11, 2020, unless city-wide flooding creates extremely hazardous driving conditions for students, parents, faculty, and staff. School district staff will continue to work with the Jacksonville Police Department, and EMA to monitor the situation overnight. In the event conditions deteriorate significantly, stakeholders will be notified as soon as possible. The safety of Jacksonville’s students is the first priority.

JHS - Jacksonville High School
September 21, 2019 at 10:59 AM ·

Russ Waits, principal of Jacksonville High School, would like to announce that Parker Comisac has been named a Commended Student in the 2020 National Merit Scholarship Program. Commended Students placed among the top 50,000 scorers of more than 1.5 million students who entered the 2020 competition by taking the 2018 Preliminary SAT/National Merit Scholarship Qualifying Test (PSAT/NMSQT). About 34,000 Commended Students throughout the nation are being recognized for their exceptional academic promise.

“Those being named Commended Students have demonstrated outstanding potential for academic success,” commented a spokesperson for NMSC (National Merit Scholarship Corporation). “These students represent a valuable national resource; recognizing their accomplishments, as well as the key role their schools play in their academic development, is vital to the advancement of educational excellence in our nation.”
